Posts.Content: Mar 12, 2015 06:11PM jnh wrote: Hi, I have been on Afinitor and Aromasin for 21 months…will be 2 years if I make it til June! 6 months ago, my onc and I decided to add Faslodex to the A/A combo because my tumor markers were rising and rising…no proof in scans of progression, though, so I didn't want to give up the A/A. Just had scans that showed NED. My tumor markers are finally stable and going down a little! I am a full-time special education teacher with a very physical job. I am also the mother of 2 very active teenage boys who both play sports. I have been able to continue all my normal activities including taking kids to sports activities, walking, and jogging. Now, some days are harder than others and I do have some fatigue. My drug of choice is caffeine. :0) I know side effects vary so much from person to person, but I think working is VERY possible! My main side effects are migraines and mouth sores. The mouth sores were the worst right at the beginning. Both have gotten fewer and milder with time. Oral prednisone with an on and off again schedule helped the most with the mouth sores-I should have started that right away. After the first few months, the mouth sores got SO much better-now I rarely take the steroids. The medication Imitrex has been a miracle drug for the migraines! I even discovered that 1/2 tablet would do the trick most of the time and so my prescription would go further for me! I also get some body aches but they are very tolerable. After about a year, I did have trouble with high blood pressure and high resting heart rate. Cardiologist said the treatment can do that. I did have to go on a small dose of a beta blocker which also makes me tired. But it took care of the problem and I'm still on the A/A combo plus Faslodex! Good luck! I hope it works for you! Julie

Posts.Content: Nov 5, 2015 07:20PM jnh wrote: I"M A TRANSFORMER!!! My cancer has changed genetically to a third type, opening new therapies. I was diagnosed stage IV in 2011 with mets to sternum and lungs. Got to NED. been through 4 treatments that all worked for approx . a year each. Now I have new liver mets. They are small, but I pushed for a biopsy…..and got a surprise! My original Stage II cancer in 2002 was triple neg. In 2011, I was ERPR+, HER-. It has changed genetically AGAIN, which is why anti-hormonal therapies stopped working! Now it is ERPR- and HER+. The good thing is that now I can try the HER2nu targeted therapies! I start Kadcyla Monday! Hoping for good things! Julie
